  "texts": [
    "Alashri et al. (2016) and Fernandez-Zubieta et al. (2022) build supervised models to detect these core framing tasks in news articles and social media posts about climate change and climate action.",
    "Social movement scholars recognize the need for empirical, large-N, and comparative framing research in addition to in-depth interpretive case studies (Snow et al., 2014), but such endeavors have been limited by the relative lack of sociologically-grounded computational approaches.",
    "Our work addresses this methodological gap and showcases the utility of computational methods for such empirical analyses.",
    "We now turn to our data collection, codebook creation, and annotation procedures.",
    "We first manually annotate framing strategies in a random sample of data in order to train models to automatically infer labels for the entire dataset of nearly two million tweets."
  ],
